    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName> Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Prime Minister’s Assistant Private Secretary</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_BFDW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Brown</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_HHL1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">most secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">most immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-02">December 2,
                            1943</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The Prime Minister has instructed me to send down to you immediately, for the
                    President’s information, the attached copy of telegram No. 365 from Angora to
                    the Minister of State, Cairo, which was repeated to Teheran and which the Prime
                    Minister saw last night, and of telegram No. 394 from Angora to the Embassy at
                    Cairo which has just been received.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BFDW1">F. D. W. <hi rend="smallcaps">Brown</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p rend="flushleft">2.12.43</p>
                </postscript>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Attachment 1]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName
                            corresp="#p_KHSH1" type="from">
                            <hi rend="italic">Knatchbull-Hugessen</hi>
                        </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the British Minister of State Resident in
                            the Middle East</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CRG1" type="to">
                            <hi rend="italic">Casey</hi>
                        </persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">most immediate</hi>
                        </seg>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-01">December 1,
                                1943</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>Addressed Minister of State telegram 365 and repeated to Tehran and Foreign
                        Office. Most secret.</p>
                    <p>Minister for Foreign Affairs<note n="2" xml:id="d426fn2">
                            <persName corresp="#p_MN1">Numan Menemencioğlu</persName>.</note>
                        spontaneously mentioned to U. S. Ambassador<note n="3" xml:id="d426fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_SLA1">Laurence A. Steinhardt</persName>.</note>
                        this morning the possibility of meeting President of the Republic<note n="4"
                            xml:id="d426fn4">
                            <persName corresp="#p_II1">Ismet Inönü</persName>.</note> with President
                            <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> and the Prime Minister.
                        He said that there would be serious difficulties about Cairo and that in any
                        case the party<note n="5" xml:id="d426fn5">Presumably the Republican
                            People’s Party.</note> would not agree to the President of the Republic
                        flying. Adana would present security difficulties, but speaking purely
                        personally and without commitment, he suggested Aleppo might be
                        possible.</p>
                    <pb facs="0767" n="663" xml:id="pg_663"/>
                    <p>2. I give this for information only. U. S. Ambassador is repeating it.<note
                            n="6" xml:id="d426fn6">See <persName corresp="#p_SLA1"
                                >Steinhardt</persName>’s telegram 1958 of December 1, 1943, 1 p.m.,
                                <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_632">p.
                            632</ref>.</note>
                    </p>
                </frus:attachment>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Attachment 2]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName
                            corresp="#p_KHSH1" type="from">
                            <hi rend="italic">Knatchbull-Hugessen</hi>
                        </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">British
                                Embassy</gloss> in Egypt</hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#left">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">most immediate</hi>
                        </seg>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-02">December 2,
                                1943</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>Addressed to Cairo Embassy telegram No. 394 repeated to the Foreign Office,
                        Tehran. Most Secret. Foreign Office telegram No. 1644 to me (repeating
                        Tehran telegram No. 33 to me).<note n="7" xml:id="d426fn7">The British
                            telegram under reference was not attached.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p>Pending the receipt of instructions by my Soviet and United States
                            Colleagues<note n="8" xml:id="d426fn8">Respectively <persName
                                corresp="#p_VSA1">Vinogradov</persName> and <persName
                                corresp="#p_SLA1">Steinhardt</persName>. See <hi rend="italic"
                                >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_633">p. 633</ref>, footnote 3.</note> I
                        have informed the Minister for Foreign Affairs of your proposal<note n="9"
                            xml:id="d426fn9">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_633"
                                >p. 633</ref>.</note> that the President should go to Cairo.</p>
                    <list>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Minister for Foreign Affairs has consulted the President and the Prime
                                Minister<note n="10" xml:id="d426fn10">Şükrü <persName
                                    corresp="#p_SS1">Saracoğlu</persName>.</note> and informs me as
                            follows.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>If the object of the visit is discussions on basis of decision[s]
                            already taken in conversations with <persName corresp="#p_SIV1"
                                >Stalin</persName> in Tehran the President would not be willing to
                            come.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>If however the object is to afford the opportunity of free equal and
                            unprejudged discussion as to the best method by which Turkey can serve
                            the common cause, the President would be willing to come accompanied by
                            Minister for Foreign Affairs.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Minister for Foreign Affairs explained that the President’s position
                            [vis-à-vis the?]<note n="11" xml:id="d426fn11">Garbled passage in source
                                text.</note> national party and the country would be rendered
                            impossible if he accepted the invitation on the basis of paragraph
                            3.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>If the invitation is on basis of paragraph 4 he would be ready to
                            leave on the morning of December 3rd reaching Adana early December 4th.
                            His party would number 15. There would in addition be my Soviet and
                            United States Colleagues and myself. I should propose to bring
                                Counsellor<note n="12" xml:id="d426fn12">
                                <persName corresp="#p_HAK1">Alexander Knox Helm</persName>.</note>
                            and Air Attaché.<note n="13" xml:id="d426fn13">Air Vice Marshal
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GRA1">Robert Allingham
                                George</persName>.</note> Including the President’s party it would
                            be necessary to count on total of 25 to 30.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>I have been in touch with my Soviet and United States Colleagues and
                            will inform them of the above as soon as possible.</item>
                    </list>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHSH1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Knatchbull Hugessen</hi>
                            </persName>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
